Two viewers per team each see one of two near-identical scenes of objects (shapes with a size and color). Objects are located only relationally — a coarse area plus what they sit near, never by coordinates — and identical objects recur, so position is what distinguishes them. The two scenes differ in a small number of planted ways (an attribute changed, an object moved, an object added, or an object removed), and neither viewer can see the other's scene or the differences. Over {{ round_count }} rounds the viewers must talk on a shared link channel under a tight character budget — too small to read a scene aloud — to ground each other on the layout, find every difference, and submit the list in plain English (a judge that never saw the chat scores it).{% if two_teams %} Two teams compete on the identical scenes each round: a team must find every difference within budget with no incorrect guesses to be eligible, and among eligible teams the one that sent the fewest characters wins.{% else %} A team must find every difference within budget with no incorrect guesses; total characters sent is the score to minimize.{% endif %}
